_teaser><wbmd_c_mini_article object_type="wbmd_cons_shrt_txt" directive="expand" chronic_id="0000000000000000"></wbmd_c_mini_article></metadata_section><content_section><cons_import_health_ref><title>General Information</title><pages><page><section_group><section_header></section_header><section_type>Vendor</section_type><section_text><a name="ncicdr0000062928-general-information"></a><p>Pheochromocytoma is a rare tumor of chromaffin cells most commonly arising from the adrenal medulla. An estimated 800 cases are diagnosed yearly in the United States. The peak incidence is in the third to fifth decades of life. Bilateral disease is present in approximately 10% of patients. Bilaterality is much more common in familial pheochromocytoma and is often found in association with the familial multiple endocrine neoplasia syndromes (MEN, types 2A and 2B). In patients with MEN type 2 syndromes, the risk of developing a contralateral tumor following unilateral adrenalectomy is approximately 50%.[<a bookmark="s2.1" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">1</a>] Other syndromes associated with pheochromocytoma include neurofibromatosis, von Hippel-<a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="32713" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001ed56" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nord/Von_Hippel_Lindau_Disease.xml" keywordId="41569" keywordSetId="10061" object_type="" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nord/Von_Hippel_Lindau_Disease.xml">Lindau disease</a>, cerebellar hemangioblastoma, Sturge-Weber syndrome, and <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="32517" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001ec48" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nord/Tuberous_Sclerosis_10961.xml" keywordId="41357" keywordSetId="10017" object_type="" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nord/Tuberous_Sclerosis_10961.xml">tuberous sclerosis</a>. In a series of 82 unselected patients with pheochromocytoma, 23% were found to be carriers of associated familial disorders.[<a bookmark="s2.2" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">2</a>] Therefore, all patients with pheochromocytomas should be screened for MEN2 and von Hippel-Lindau disease to avert further morbidity and mortality in the patients and their families. Extra-adrenal pheochromocytoma or functional paraganglioma occurs in approximately 10% to 15% of cases and may arise from any extra-adrenal chromaffin tissue in the body associated with sympathetic ganglia. </p><p>Extra-adrenal pheochromocytoma is most often located within the abdomen and may have greater malignant potential than adrenal pheochromocytoma.[<a bookmark="s2.3" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">3</a>,<a bookmark="s2.4" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">4</a>] Extra-adrenal tumors usually have a poorer prognosis than adrenal tumors.[<a bookmark="s2.3" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">3</a>,<a bookmark="s2.4" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">4</a>] In one series of 73 patients referred to tertiary care centers, however, no difference was found in the metastatic potential or the prognosis of extra-adrenal tumors compared to adrenal tumors.[<a bookmark="s2.5" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">5</a>] Because of the production and release of <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="34192" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001f06d" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Catecholamines_14697.xml" keywordId="8402" keywordSetId="1948" object_type="" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Catecholamines_14697.xml">catecholamines</a>, pheochromocytomas <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="31519" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="4E118B21F60E42BC" href="http://www.webmd.com/hypertension-high-blood-pressure/guide/hypertension-overview-facts" keywordId="32461" keywordSetId="8303" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/hypertension-high-blood-pressure/guide/hypertension-overview-facts">cause hypertension</a>. Only 0.1% to 0.5% of all <a chronic_id="091e9c5e800232f5" crossLinkId="536" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e800232f5" href="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Hypertension Health Center/page_Hypertension Health Center_091e9c5e800232f5.xml" keywordId="7630" keywordSetId="1371" object_type="wbmd_pb_page" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Hypertension Health Center/page_Hypertension Health Center_091e9c5e800232f5.xml">hypertension</a> patients, however, will be found to have a pheochromocytoma. The importance of the recognition of this disease is that more than 90% of patients properly diagnosed and treated are curable.[<a bookmark="s2.4" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">4</a>,<a bookmark="s2.6" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">6</a>,<a bookmark="s2.7" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">7</a>,<a bookmark="s2.8" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">8</a>,<a bookmark="s2.9" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">9</a>,<a bookmark="s2.10" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">10</a>]</p><p>The hypertension caused by pheochromocytoma may be sustained or paroxysmal and is often severe with occasional malignant features of encephalopathy, retinopathy, and proteinuria. Less commonly, severe hypertensive reactions may occur during incidental surgery, following trauma, <a chronic_id="091e9c5e80044b2e" crossLinkId="501" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e80044b2e" href="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Health and Fitness Center TOC Page/page_Health and Fitness Center_091e9c5e80044b2e.xml" keywordId="35030" keywordSetId="8746" object_type="wbmd_pb_page" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Health and Fitness Center TOC Page/page_Health and Fitness Center_091e9c5e80044b2e.xml">exercise</a>, or micturition (in the setting of bladder pheochromocytoma) when the diagnosis is unsuspected. Other clinical features of pheochromocytoma include <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8002394a" crossLinkId="189" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8002394a" href="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/MigrainesHeadaches Health Center/page_Migraines and Headaches Health Center_091e9c5e8002394a.xml" keywordId="7521" keywordSetId="1291" object_type="wbmd_pb_page" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/MigrainesHeadaches Health Center/page_Migraines and Headaches Health Center_091e9c5e8002394a.xml">headache</a>, sweating, palpitation, tachycardia, and severe <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8003c115" crossLinkId="452" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8003c115" href="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Anxiety and Panic Disorders Health Center TOC/page_Anxiety and Panic Disorders Health Center_091e9c5e8003c115.xml" keywordId="31072" keywordSetId="8074" object_type="wbmd_pb_page" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Anxiety and Panic Disorders Health Center TOC/page_Anxiety and Panic Disorders Health Center_091e9c5e8003c115.xml">anxiety</a> along with epigastric or <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="47596" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001e4ea" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/symptom/Chest_Pain-Topic_Overview.xml" keywordId="32938" keywordSetId="8361" object_type="" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/symptom/Chest_Pain-Topic_Overview.xml">chest pain</a>. Orthostatic hypotension is frequently present and is probably caused by reduced intravascular volume following chronic adrenergic stimulation. </p><p>The diagnosis of pheochromocytoma is established by the demonstration of elevated 24-hour urinary excretion of free catecholamines (norepinephrine and <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="64627" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="93171" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-93171-epinephrine+im.aspx" keywordId="53106" keywordSetId="20715" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-93171-epinephrine+im.aspx">epinephrine</a>) or catecholamine metabolites (vanillylmandelic acid and total metanephrines). The measurement of plasma catecholamines can also be of value in the diagnosis of pheochromocytoma. The measurement of plasma catecholamines, however, has limited sensitivity and specificity. Plasma metanephrines have been reported to be more sensitive than plasma catecholamines. When 52 patients with pheochromocytoma were studied, every patient was found to have elevated plasma levels of metanephrines, but eight of the patients had normal levels of plasma catecholamines.[<a bookmark="s2.11" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">11</a>] Pharmacologic testing with agents such as glucagon or <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="31211" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="11754" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-11754-Clonidine+Oral.aspx?drugid=11754&amp;drugname=Clonidine+Oral" keywordId="7129" keywordSetId="1005" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-11754-Clonidine+Oral.aspx?drugid=11754&amp;drugname=Clonidine+Oral">clonidine</a> is rarely required to make the diagnosis.[<a bookmark="s2.12" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">12</a>,<a bookmark="s2.13" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">13</a>]</p></section_text></section_group></page><page><section_group><section_header is_continued="true"> continued...</section_header><section_type>Vendor</section_type><section_text><p>Once the diagnosis is confirmed by biochemical determinations, the localization and extent of disease should be determined.[<a bookmark="s2.9" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">9</a>] Ninety-seven percent of the tumors are found in the abdomen, 2% to 3% are found in the thorax, and 1% are found in the neck. The initial studies should be a chest film and abdominal computed tomographic (CT) scan. I<sup>131</sup> meta-iodobenzylguanidine (MIBG) has been found to be useful as a scintigraphic localization agent.[<a bookmark="s2.14" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">14</a>,<a bookmark="s2.15" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">15</a>] If the tumor is not adequately localized by these methods, then <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="42645" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001f07f" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Magnetic_Resonance_Imaging_MRI.xml" keywordId="7831" keywordSetId="1521" object_type="" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Magnetic_Resonance_Imaging_MRI.xml">magnetic resonance imaging</a> (<a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="42645" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001f07f" href="http://www.webmd.com/a-to-z-guides/magnetic-resonance-imaging-mri" keywordId="37777" keywordSetId="7728" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/a-to-z-guides/magnetic-resonance-imaging-mri">MRI</a>), or rarely, vena cava catheterization with selective venous sampling for catecholamines may be indicated.[<a bookmark="s2.16" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">16</a>] CT and MRI scans are about equally sensitive (98% to 100%), while MIBG scanning has a sensitivity of only 80%. MIBG scanning, however, has a specificity of 100%, compared to a specificity of 70% for CT and MRI.[<a bookmark="s2.12" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">12</a>] If extra-adrenal or metastatic disease is suspected, additional studies such as <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="50642" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001f08b" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Bone_Scan.xml" keywordId="6994" keywordSetId="907" object_type="" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Bone_Scan.xml">bone scan</a>, liver-<a chronic_id="091e9c5e8034e3f1" crossLinkId="70311" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8034e3f1" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/image_collections/anatomy_pages/picture_of_the_spleen.xml" keywordId="58452" keywordSetId="25861" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/image_collections/anatomy_pages/picture_of_the_spleen.xml">spleen</a> scan, chest <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="44946" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001f058" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Computed_Tomography_CT_Scan_of_the_Body.xml" keywordId="7212" keywordSetId="1060" object_type="" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Computed_Tomography_CT_Scan_of_the_Body.xml">CT scan</a>, or <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="43076" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8001f05c" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Doppler_Ultrasound.xml" keywordId="41424" keywordSetId="10032" object_type="" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/medicaltest/Doppler_Ultrasound.xml">ultrasound</a> may aid in determining the extent of disease. </p><p>Surgical resection is the standard curative modality.[<a bookmark="s2.17" document-type="Nci" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml" directive="friendlyurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e800f418c" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/nci/ncicdr0000062928-General_Information.xml">17</a>] If the primary tumor is localized to the adrenal gland and is benign, then survival is that of the normal age-matched population. In patients with unresectable, recurrent, or metastatic disease, long-term survival is possible; the overall 5-year survival, however, is less than 50%. Pharmacologic treatment of the catecholamine excess is mandatory and surgery, <a chronic_id="091e9c5e804d6f9a" crossLinkId="1049001" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e804d6f9a" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/cancer/miscellaneous/what_to_expect_from_radiation_therapy.xml" keywordId="61840" keywordSetId="27679" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/cancer/miscellaneous/what_to_expect_from_radiation_therapy.xml">radiation</a> therapy, or chemotherapy may provide palliative benefit. </p><p><b>References:</b><br></p><ol><li><a name="s2.1"></a> Lairmore TC, Ball DW, Baylin SB, et al.: Management of pheochromocytomas in patients with multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2 syndromes. Ann Surg 217 (6): 595-601; discussion 601-3, 1993.</li><li><a name="s2.2"></a> Neumann HP, Berger DP, Sigmund G, et al.: Pheochromocytomas, multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2, and von Hippel-Lindau disease. N Engl J Med 329 (21): 1531-8, 1993.</li><li><a name="s2.3"></a> Sclafani LM, Woodruff JM, Brennan MF: Extraadrenal retroperitoneal paragangliomas: natural history and response to treatment. Surgery 108 (6): 1124-9; discussion 1129-30, 1990.</li><li><a name="s2.4"></a> Whalen RK, Althausen AF, Daniels GH: Extra-adrenal pheochromocytoma. J Urol 147 (1): 1-10, 1992.</li><li><a name="s2.5"></a> Pommier RF, Vetto JT, Billingsly K, et al.: Comparison of adrenal and extraadrenal pheochromocytomas. Surgery 114 (6): 1160-5; discussion 1165-6, 1993.</li><li><a name="s2.6"></a> Manger WM, Gifford RW: Pheochromocytoma. New York: Springer-Verlag, 1977.</li><li><a name="s2.7"></a> Norton JA: Adrenal tumors. In: DeVita VT Jr, Hellman S, Rosenberg SA, eds.: <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="31192" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="9A13E96B1FF14D08" href="http://www.webmd.com/cancer/" keywordId="7043" keywordSetId="942" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/cancer/">Cancer</a>: Principles and Practice of Oncology. 7th ed. Philadelphia, Pa: Lippincott Williams &amp;amp; Wilkins, 2005, pp 1528-39.</li><li><a name="s2.8"></a> Young JB, Landsberg L: Catecholamines and the adrenal medulla: pheochromocytoma. In: Wilson JD, Foster DW, Kronenberg HM, et al., eds.: Williams Textbook of Endocrinology. 9th ed. Philadelphia, Pa: W.B. Saunders Company, 1998, pp 705-716.</li><li><a name="s2.9"></a> Bravo EL, Gifford RW Jr: Current concepts. Pheochromocytoma: diagnosis, localization and management. N Engl J Med 311 (20): 1298-303,